    {
      "step_id": "f7aa52e9",
      "step_index": 3,
      "step_type": "reasoning",
      "content": "### 2) SAR REASONING (why these features push hERG risk up/down)\n**Features increasing hERG blockade likelihood**\n- **Cationic amine at physiological pH:** hERG blockers often bind via **electrostatic interaction** between a **protonated amine** and residues in the inner cavity (commonly discussed: interaction network near the selectivity filter/cavity; aromatic residues enable \u03c0 interactions).\n- **Large aromatic/hydrophobic surface:** The fused aromatic system can engage in **\u03c0\u2013\u03c0 / hydrophobic interactions** with key aromatic residues in the hERG cavity (classically Tyr/Phe lining the pore). Polycyclic aromatics are frequently \u201csticky\u201d for hERG.\n- **Rigid scaffold:** Conformational restriction can **pre-organize** the ligand into a binding-competent pose, sometimes increasing affinity if the geometry matches the cavity.",
      "tool_name": null,
      "tool_input": null,
      "tool_output": null,
