    {
      "step_id": "bbbeef70",
      "step_index": 6,
      "step_type": "reasoning",
      "content": "### 3) MECHANISTIC BASIS (how it would interact with hERG)\n- hERG blockers typically access the **intracellular cavity** and bind in the **central pore region**, stabilized by:\n  - **Ion-pair / electrostatic attraction**: **protonated tertiary amine** to polar/negative field in the cavity.\n  - **Aromatic/hydrophobic contacts**: the ligand\u2019s aromatic system packs against **aromatic residues** lining the cavity (often cited: **Y652/F656** in hERG S6 as major contributors to many blockers).\n- This molecule offers:\n  - A **protonatable tertiary N** positioned close to the polycyclic core (good for the canonical \u201cbasic center + hydrophobes\u201d arrangement).\n  - A **broad aromatic face** that can form stabilizing \u03c0/hydrophobic contacts.\n- The **rigid 3D topology** could fit well into the cavity (promoting binding) or could clash if the curvature/exit vectors don\u2019t align\u2014this is the main uncertainty.",
